⸻

1. Purpose

This document defines the permanent system principles of Numera.

These principles must guide every future decision in product, architecture, AI, data, integrations, security and user experience.

The objective is to prevent Numera from becoming complex, inconsistent or opaque as it grows.

⸻

2. Core System Belief

Numera must remain simple for the user, even if the internal system becomes complex.

The user should never feel the complexity of OCR, AI models, accounting rules, integrations, memory, permissions or data pipelines.

Complexity belongs inside the system.

Clarity belongs in the interface.

⸻

3. Principle 1 — Understand Before Automating

Numera must never automate a process it does not understand.

Before acting, Numera must know:

* what information it has;
* what information is missing;
* what confidence level exists;
* what risk exists;
* whether human approval is required.

Automation without understanding is not allowed.

⸻

4. Principle 2 — One Source of Truth

Every relevant piece of information must have one authoritative source.

Duplicated data creates inconsistency.

When data appears in multiple places, Numera must know which source is authoritative.

Examples:

* invoice data;
* supplier records;
* accounting entries;
* memories;
* rules;
* user permissions;
* company configuration.

⸻

5. Principle 3 — Explain Every Important Decision

Every important recommendation or action must be explainable.

Numera must be able to answer:

* why this decision was proposed;
* what data was used;
* what rules were applied;
* what memory influenced the result;
* what confidence level exists;
* what alternatives were considered.

A decision that cannot be explained should not be automated.

⸻

6. Principle 4 — Memory Must Be Visible and Editable

Memory is a strategic advantage, but hidden memory is dangerous.

Every relevant memory must be:

* visible;
* traceable;
* editable;
* reversible;
* auditable.

The user must be able to understand what Numera remembers and why.

⸻

7. Principle 5 — Ask Before Assuming

When confidence is low or risk is meaningful, Numera must ask.

Guessing is not intelligence.

The system should prefer a short question over a silent incorrect action.

⸻

8. Principle 6 — Rules and AI Must Be Separated

Business rules must not be buried inside AI prompts or model behaviour.

Rules must be explicit, testable and versioned.

AI may interpret context, but rules define boundaries.

This separation allows Numera to remain reliable even when AI models change.

⸻

9. Principle 7 — Integrations Must Be Replaceable

Numera must not depend permanently on a single ERP, OCR provider, LLM provider, database vendor or cloud provider.

External systems must be connected through replaceable interfaces.

This makes Numera resilient and future-proof.

⸻

10. Principle 8 — The LLM Is Not the Brain

The brain of Numera is not a language model.

The brain is the decision system composed of:

* Memory Engine;
* Knowledge Graph;
* Rule Engine;
* Confidence Engine;
* AI Orchestrator;
* Action Planner;
* Reflection Engine.

The LLM is one tool used by the system, not the system itself.

⸻

11. Principle 9 — Human Approval for High-Risk Actions

Any action with fiscal, legal, accounting, banking or irreversible impact must require explicit human approval.

Numera may prepare.

Numera may recommend.

Numera may explain.

But the user approves high-risk execution.

⸻

12. Principle 10 — Every Action Must Leave a Trace

Every relevant action must be logged.

The system must record:

* who initiated the action;
* when it happened;
* what data was used;
* what rule or model was involved;
* what confidence level existed;
* whether the action was approved, rejected or corrected.

Traceability is part of the product.

⸻

13. Principle 11 — The User Should Not Repeat Work

If the user has already corrected, approved or configured something, Numera should remember it when appropriate.

Repeated manual work is a product failure.

The system should learn from approved user behaviour.

⸻

14. Principle 12 — Simplicity Beats Feature Count

Numera will not compete by having more screens or buttons.

Numera will compete by reducing the number of actions needed to complete financial work.

A feature that increases complexity without clear value must be rejected.

⸻

15. Principle 13 — Data Belongs to the Company

Company knowledge belongs to the company.

Numera must not treat customer data, memories or rules as proprietary black-box behaviour.

Where possible, company knowledge should be exportable, reviewable and portable.

⸻

16. Principle 14 — Confidence Must Be Explicit

Numera must show confidence levels where they affect user trust or risk.

The system must distinguish between:

* known;
* inferred;
* uncertain;
* missing;
* conflicting.

This prevents false certainty.

⸻

17. Principle 15 — Reflection Is Required for Learning

Numera must not only act.

It must evaluate whether its action was useful.

Every accepted, corrected or rejected recommendation should inform future behaviour.

Reflection converts usage into learning.

⸻

18. Principle 16 — The Interface Is an Intelligence Layer

The interface should not merely display data.

It should explain what deserves attention.

Numera should not show a dashboard full of numbers when it can say:

“These three issues require review today.”

Home Intelligence is preferred over static dashboards.

⸻

19. Principle 17 — Conversation Is Navigation

Users should be able to access information by asking natural questions.

Search, filters and tables remain useful, but conversation should become the primary way to explore company knowledge.

Examples:

* “Show me all Vodafone invoices from last year.”
* “Which suppliers increased prices this quarter?”
* “What should I review before closing the month?”

⸻

20. Principle 18 — Internal Complexity Must Be Modular

As Numera grows, complexity must be isolated into modules.

No module should become a hidden dependency for the entire platform.

Core modules must communicate through clear interfaces.

⸻

21. Principle 19 — Quality Over Speed

Fast development is valuable only if it does not create future fragility.

Numera must avoid short-term decisions that make the product harder to understand, test or evolve.

⸻

22. Principle 20 — Every System Decision Must Survive Scale

A decision that works for one company but breaks for one thousand companies is not a good system decision.

Numera must be designed for:

* multi-company;
* multi-user;
* multi-role;
* multi-integration;
* multi-country future expansion.

⸻

23. Enforcement

These principles must be applied during:

* product design;
* architecture reviews;
* AI design;
* database modelling;
* UX design;
* API design;
* code review;
* security review;
* roadmap prioritisation.

If a proposed decision violates these principles, it must be rejected or formally justified in a Decision Log entry.

⸻

24. Closing Statement

Numera must remain intelligent, trustworthy and simple as it grows.

The purpose of these principles is to protect the product from becoming another complex financial system.

Numera should feel like a financial assistant.

Not like an ERP.

Not like a database.

Not like a collection of features.

A system that understands, remembers, explains and helps people decide.